	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>DRC’s extensive import controls fail to protect agriculture</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the latest WTO Trade Policy Review for the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), agricultural imports are subject to a multitude of levies and taxes, as well as to cumbersome formalities in addition to an average tariff of 10%. Yet ‘the levies imposed by various bodies on both imports and exports are often superfluous.’ Consequently, the level of protection provided to the sector is less than ‘the authorities believe they are providing for domestic producers.’</p><p>The report notes that ‘the most prejudicial effect of the plethora of inspections and taxes’ is the length of time it takes to complete formalities. This has knock-on effects on regional trade. The cost of transport from Bukavu to Mombasa, for example, is US$220/tonne which is around twice the cost from Kigali to Mombasa – virtually the same distance.</p><p>The DRC has ‘a vast agricultural potential’ with natural resources and a climate that favours a range of activities. But for several decades the DRC’s agricultural productivity has been in almost constant decline, with a steep regression in perennial and industrial crops. Agriculture’s share of GDP has fallen from an estimated at 70% in 1980 to 50% in 2000. This is ‘reflected in a lack of food security, malnutrition, a shortage of high‑quality seed, rising prices, and a failure to develop the processing and preservation of agricultural and fishery products.’</p><p>The competitiveness of agricultural and agro‑industrial enterprises is being eroded by the low level of productivity of skilled and unskilled labour; the low level of agricultural productivity due to the difficulty in obtaining access to improved plant and animal material and other inputs; the high cost and unreliability of their energy supplies; and the difficulty in obtaining the credit/financing required to modernise their production plant. The relatively low use of fertilisers and pesticides as well as other agricultural inputs, all of which are imported, occurs despite the fact that the nominal tariff on inputs is low, at 5%. This is partly because imported inputs are also subject to several other levies and taxes. Moreover, the government has responsibility for production, importation, exportation, packaging, storage and distribution of fertiliser.</p><p>A comprehensive package of reform measures is contained in a draft law on the Agricultural Code which is currently under discussion in the DRC parliament. These measures aim to attract private investment, in particular, by introducing fiscal reforms and rationalisation, including the establishment of single window systems. They also refocus the state’s mission in the sector and transfer responsibility for the design and implementation of agricultural programmes to the provincial level. And they aim to promote and strengthen partnerships between the state and non‑state players, as well as facilitating agricultural employment and training and access to credit. The government also plans to promote the national agricultural extension and research programme, which is aimed at improving technical and, in some cases, financial assistance for farmers.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Democratic Republic of the Congo’, 24 and 26 November 2010 <br/>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp340_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp340_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The regular Trade Policy Reviews undertaken jointly by the WTO Secretariat and member governments provide a great deal of information on how agricultural trade operates in practice. They illuminate many areas. Two that apply not only in the DRC but also much more widely are the discrepancy between what governments think their policies are doing for agricultural production and trade and what is actually happening; and that tariffs are far from the only measure affecting agricultural exports and imports. The net effect, in the view of the TPR authors, is to depress production in a country that has the potential to be a very substantial surplus producer.</p><p>It is also clear from the TPR that trade policy is far from the major, still less the only, area of government policy that affects a sector such as agriculture. Non-trade (and non-agricultural) policies are extremely important. The catchphrase ‘mainstreaming trade policy’ reflects this fact. If a government’s policies on trade do not point in the same direction as all of its other policies that affect production (which must also be coherent), the net effect will be very different from what might be expected. It is important to keep this context constantly in mind when assessing the potential impact of any change to a country’s agricultural trade policy (during the course, for example, of a trade negotiation). That impact will be heavily influenced by what the government does (or does not do) in the many non-trade policies affecting the sector.</p>
		</div>
		
